Sport Vouchers Program Analysis¶

The goal of this Portfolio task is to explore data from the Federal Government Sport Vouchers program - this is a program that provides up to two $100 vouchers for kids to participate in organised sport. Here's the NSW Active Kids page, there are similar schemes in other states - this data is from South Australia.

This is an exercise in exploring data and communicating the insights you can gain from it. The source data comes from the data.gov.au website and provides details of all Sport Vouchers that have been redeemed since February in SA 2015 as part of the Sport Voucher program: Sports Vouchers Data. This download is provided for you as sportsvouchersclaimed.csv.

To augment this data you can also make use of ABS SEIFA data by LGA which shows a few measures of Socioeconomic Advantage and Disadvantage for every Local Government Area. This data is provided for you as ABS_SEIFA_LGA.csv. This could enable you to answer questions about whether the voucher program is used equally by parents in low, middle and high socioeconomic areas. You might be interested in this if you were concerned that this kind of program might just benifit parents who are already advantaged (they might already be paying for sport so this program wouldn't be helping much).

Questions:

  • Describe the distribution of vouchers by: LGA, Sport - which regions/sports stand out?
  • Are some sports more popular in different parts of the state?
  • Are any LGA's over/under represented in their use of vouchers?
  • Is there a relationship between any of the SEIFA measures and voucher use in an LGA?

A challenge in this task is to display a useful summary of the data given that there are a large number of LGAs and sports involved. Try to avoid long lists and large tables. Think about what plots and tables communicate the main points of your findings.

The SEIFA data includes row for each Local Government Area (LGA) but the names of the LGAs have a letter or letters in brackets after the name. To allow us to match this up with the voucher data we remove this and convert to uppercase.

For each LGA the data includes a number of measures all of which could be useful in your exploration.

In [4]:
# read the SEIFA data, create an LGA column by removing the letters in brackets and converting to uppercase

lga = seifa["Local Government Areas - 2011"].str.replace(' \([ACSRCDMT]+\)', '').str.upper()
seifa['LGA'] = lga

Since there are many rows per LGA we need to use pivot_table to create a new data frame with one row per LGA. Here is an example of doing this to create a table with the different SCORE measures and the population (URP) field.

Data Cleaning¶

The 9460 null values were identified within the "sa_voushers_scores" pivot table under the SEIFA table attributes. This was a result of 8835 tuples with mismatching LGA names between the SEIFA and SA Voucher data tables. Also 625 tuples had "NO LGA" listed.

The following steps were taken to clean the data:

  1. Of the 625 "NO LGA" tuples, 30 of the tuples contained data , such as "Participant_Suburb, from which the LGA could be dervived. As the number was so small all tuples with "NO LGA" in the "Participant_LGA" field were deleted.
  2. The Adelaide Plains LGA changed its name from Mallala LGA in 2016. The SEIFA data reported all data under Mallala LGA. The SEIFA table was updated by changing "MALLALA" to "ADELAIDE PLAINS". This rectified 899 errors.
  3. "BERRI BARMERA" was "BERRI AND BARMERA" in the SEIFA data. The name was changed in the SEIFA data and rectified 1486 errors.
  4. In the SEIFA data "LIGHT" was followed by (RegC). The (RegC) was removed which rectified 2066 errors.
  5. "NARACOORTE LUCINDALE" was "NARACOORTE AND LUCINDALE" in the SEIFA data. The name was changed in the SEIFA data and rectified 1097 errors.
  6. "NORWOOD PAYNEHAM AND ST PETERS" was "NORWOOD PAYNEHAM ST PETERS" in the SEIFA data. The name was changed in the SEIFA data and rectified 1352 errors.
  7. "PORT PERIE" WAS "PORT PERIE CITY AND DISTS" in the SEIFA data. The name was changed in the SEIFA data and rectified 1935 errors.
  8. Kingston is a district council in South Australia and a city in Victoria. The "KINGSTON (C)" (Victorian city) was dropped from the SEIFA Data. This resolved the created in the calculation of the total population.

2.3 Data Acronyms and Indexes¶

Sports Vouchers Data

Metadata

Club_Previous_Member: Categorises the participant as new (not registered) or returning (registered) participant of the activity provider

Participant_ATSI_Indicator: Categorises the participant as identifying with aboriginal or Torres Strait Island heritage (ATSI), or not (Not ATSI)

Participant_CALD_Indicator: Categorises the participant as identifying with a non-Australian cultural background (CALD) or not (Not CALD)

Voucher_Value: Value of the voucher redeemed by the participant (Maximum $50 AUD per annum)

SEIFA data by LGA

SEIFA Summary

The four SEIFA indexes include:

Index of Education and Occupation (IEO): an index which reflects the educational and occupational levels of communities. Low score indicates lower education and occupation status of people in the area. High score indicates higher education and occupation status of people in the area.

Index of Economic Resources (IER): an index which focuses on the relative aspects of socio-economic adnavtage and disadvantage by summarising income and wealth related variables. Low score indicates a relative lack of access to economic resources. High score indicates relatively greater access to economic resources.

Index of Relative Socio-Economic Advantage and Disadvantage (IRSAD): an index which summarises the economic andsocial conditions of people and households within an area. Low score indicates relatively greater disadvantage and a lack of advantage in general. high score indicates a relative lack of disadvantage and greater advantage in general.

Index of Relative Socio-Economic Disadvantage (IRSD): an index which summarises the economic and social conditions of people and households within an area. low score indicates relatively greater disadvantage. high score indicates a relative lack of disadvantage.

2.8 Relationships between SEIFA measures and voucher use¶

Is there a relationship between any of the SEIFA measures and voucher use in an LGA?

In [45]:
#pair plot to compare relationships between voucher use and SEIFA measures
lga_stats.drop(columns='Vouchers_PP', inplace = True)
sns.pairplot(lga_stats)
Out[45]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.PairGrid at 0x16811ab30d0>

A number of positive linear relationships exist between a number of the SEIFA measures. With regards to vouchers claimed there is a positive linear relationship between number of vouchers claimed and population. No linear relationship appears to exist between number of vouchers claimed and other SEIFA measures. Strong and moderate positive linear relationships can be observed between SEIFA measures.

In [46]:
#correlation matrix
sns.heatmap(lga_stats.corr(), annot=True)
Out[46]:
<AxesSubplot:>

The correlation matrix shows a strong positive correlation between number of vouchers claimed and population. No correlation (minimal) was observed between SEIFA measures and number of vouchers claimed.

Based on the pairplot and correlation matrix the SEIFA measures could not be used to accurately predict number of vouchers claimed by an LGA.

2.9 Challenge - Queensland¶

Note: this is an extra task that you might take on to get a better grade for your portfolio. You can get a good pass grade without doing this.

Queensland has a similar program called Get Started and we can retrieve data from their program in a similar format.

The file round1-redeemed_get_started_vouchers.csv contains records of the vouchers issued in Queensland. The date of this data is not included but the program started in 2015 so it is probably from around then.

The data includes the LGA of the individual but the name of the activity is slightly different. To do a comparable analysis you would need to map the activity names onto those from South Australia.
